<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:132439" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex octospinosa var. pallida Crawley" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="octospinosa" variety="pallida">Acromyrmex octospinosa, Reich., var. pallida</taxonomicName>
, nov.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="92">[[worker]] major. Entirely pale yellow; antennae deeper yellow, teeth of mandibles dark brown or black.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="92">[[worker]] minima. Slightly deeper in colour than the [[worker]] major.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="92">
In both [[worker]] major and minima the spines are somewhat thinner and shorter than in the type, but otherwise, with the exception of the colour, the 
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="variety">new variety</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to the type.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageNumber="92">
Issororo, British Guiana, 1918 (Bodkin, no. 422). Nest in soil under a rock. The ants were associated with three 
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
of coccid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
